article.description: Pau Gasol scored 20 points and Shane Battier added 19 to help the host Memphis Grizzlies extend their winning streak to six games with an 84-76 victory over the New Orleans Hornets on Friday.
article.headline: Memphis rises a game above .500 for first time this season
article.linkText: Grizz thump Hornets for sixth straight victory
article.story:
MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- A night after soundly defeating the defending NBA champs on the road, the Memphis Grizzlies extended their winning streak to a season-high six games with a victory over the league's worst team. Pau Gasol scored 20 points and Shane Battier added 19 to help the Grizzlies defeat the New Orleans Hornets 84-76 Friday night. Memphis outscored New Orleans 8-1 in the final 2:23 to improve to 18-17, the first time the Grizzlies have been above .500 this season. Friday's win followed Thursday's 101-79 victory over the Detroit Pistons. The Hornets dropped to an NBA-worst 2-29 with their 10th straight loss. "We knew it was going to be an ugly game," said Memphis center Lorenzen Wright, who grabbed 10 rebounds. "They're hungry, and they want to get a win bad. ...We felt this was a game we were going to win. The demeanor of the team never changed. We just knew we had to play defense and stop them." Gasol added 11 rebounds, and Battier matched his season-high with 10 rebounds. He also had a career-high five blocks. The fourth period fit Wright's description as the two teams went scoreless for more than four minutes. The Grizzlies shot 22 percent in the period, only slightly better than the Hornets' 20 percent. New Orleans also had six turnovers in the fourth. The Hornets, despite not making a field goal in the final seven minutes, closed within a point twice in the fourth quarter, the final time at 76-75 on Rodney Rogers' two free throws with 2:23 left. From there, Memphis put together six straight points as part of its closing stretch. "I don't know what it is, but we're not playing smart," Rogers said. Mike Miller finished with 16 points for Memphis. Baron Davis led the Hornets with 19 points and eight assists, but was 6-of-20 from the field. The Hornets shot a season-low 31.7 percent -- quite an accomplishment for a team that began the night with the league's worst field goal percentage, 39.7 percent. "It's not like we're not getting the looks," Davis said. "We're getting the looks. We're just not making our shots. Once again, I thought we settled for threes." Lee Nailon added 14 points, and Rogers and P.J. Brown finished with 10 points. Brown also had 12 rebounds. Memphis coach Mike Fratello acknowledged the wounded Hornets presented "the worst game you can have" after Thursday's win at Detroit. "We were fortunate," Fratello said. "I commend New Orleans for their effort. They've had a difficult season, but they didn't give up and played hard."

Game notes
Fratello's voice was hoarse before the game. "That's what happens when you miss training camp," he said, referring to taking over the team in December after Hubie Brown's retirement. ... Grizzlies F Brian Cardinal missed his third game because of a shoulder injury. Fratello said Cardinal was able to raise his right arm above shoulder level with a basketball -- an improvement -- in recent days. ... Hornets F George Lynch did not play. Lynch missed five games with a right foot injury before dressing for Wednesday's game against the Chicago Bulls. ... Hornets G Dan Dickau had a career-high six rebounds. ... Miller and Gasol made $1,000-per-point donations to UNICEF for the Indian Ocean tsunami relief efforts. ... Miller ran into Rogers' pick at midcourt late in the first half, sending the Memphis guard to the floor. Miller was led off the court, but returned to start the half. Replays showed the pick included a shoulder that struck Miller in the head. "Whatever it was, it hit hard," Miller said afterward, still rubbing his head.
